ewtheorem*{remark}{Remark}  egin{document} \sloppy 	itle{Conjectures About Cyclic Numbers: Resolutions and Counterexamples} \author{Hieu Le Duc \ Telecom SudParis \ 	exttt{duc-hieu.le@telecom-sudparis.eu}} \date{} \maketitle  egin{abstract} We settle 22 conjectures of Cohen about cyclic numbers (positive integers $n$ with $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))=1$), proving 16 and disproving 6, and we completely resolve a related OEIS problem about sequences whose running averages are Fibonacci numbers. Highlights include: asymptotics for cyclics between consecutive squares with a second-order term (Conj.~9), Legendre- and $k$-fold Oppermann-type results in short quadratic intervals (Conj.~6, Conj.~20, and twin cyclics between cubes, Conj.~32), gap and growth analogs (Visser, Rosser, Ishikawa, and a sum-3-versus-sum-2 inequality; Conj.~47,~52,~54,~56), limiting ratios (Vrba and Hassani; Conj.~60,~61), and structure results for Sophie Germain cyclics (Conj.~36,~37). We also resolve two Firoozbakht-type conjectures for cyclics (Conj.~41--42). On the negative side we exhibit counterexamples to the Panaitopol, Dusart, and Carneiro analogs (Conj.~59,~53,~50--51). Finally, for the lexicographically least sequence of pairwise distinct positive integers whose running averages are Fibonacci numbers (\seqnum{A248982}), we give explicit closed forms for all $n$ and prove Fried's Conjecture~2 asserting the disjointness of the parity-defined value sets (equivalently, $F_{n+2}+2nF_{n+1}$ is never a Fibonacci number). Proofs in this paper were assisted by GPT-5. \end{abstract} \section{Introduction} An integer $n\ge1$ is \emph{cyclic} if every group of order $n$ is cyclic. By Szele \cite{Szele1947}, this is equivalent to $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))=1$, where $\varphi$ is Euler's totient function. Let $C$ denote the set of cyclic numbers, let $C(x):=\#\{c\in C: c\le x\}$ be its counting function, and let $(c_n)_{n\ge1}$ be the increasing enumeration of $C$.  egin{remark} Two immediate consequences of Szele's criterion will be used repeatedly: (i) $2$ is the only even cyclic integer (if $n$ is even and $n>2$, then $2\mid n$ and $2\mid \varphi(n)$, so $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))\ge2$); (ii) $1$ is the only square in $C$ (if $n$ is a square $>1$, then $p\mid n$ and $p\mid \varphi(n)$ for some prime $p$, so again $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))>1$). All odd primes are cyclic since $\gcd(p,\varphi(p))=\gcd(p,p-1)=1$. \end{remark} Many conjectures about cyclics proposed by Cohen \cite{Cohen2025} are analogs of well-known results or conjectures for the prime numbers (sequence \seqnum{A000040}), with $C$ playing the role of $\mathbb P$. In this paper we give complete proofs or counterexamples to several of these conjectures, and we give a full resolution of an OEIS problem about running averages equaling Fibonacci numbers (sequence \seqnum{A248982}). Throughout, we emphasize exactly which conjectures are settled and how. \subsection*{Notation} We write $\mathcal P$ for the set of primes. For $z\ge2$ let \[ P(z):=\prod_{p\le z}p,\qquad P^-(n):=\min\{p\in\mathcal P: p\mid n\},\quad P^-(1):=\infty. \] For primes $p\le q$ we use the arrow notation $p	o q$ to mean $q\equiv1\pmod p$. We also use $\log_1 x:=\log x$, $\log_2 x:=\log\log x$, and $\log_3 x:=\log\log\log x$ when needed. \subsection*{Uniform tools and ranges} We record the uniform forms used repeatedly in the proofs; precise references are indicated.  egin{itemize} \item Linear Selberg sieve (dimension 1; consecutive integers). For $x\ge2$, $H\ge1$, $z\ge2$, letting $S((x,x+H);z):=\#\{m\in(x,x+H)\cap\mathbb N: P^-(m)\ge z\}$, one has uniformly \[ S((x,x+H);z)\ge H\prod_{p<z}\Bigl(1- rac1p\Bigr)\ -\ C\,z^2, \] for an absolute constant $C>0$; see, e.g., Halberstam--Richert \cite[Th.~2.3, Th.~2.4]{HalRich1974} or Iwaniec--Kowalski \cite[\S11.1]{IK2004}. In particular, with $z=x^{\delta}(\log x)^{-B}$ and $H\asymp x^{1/2}$ the remainder is $o(\sqrt x/\log x)$. \item $ eta$-sieve, dimension 2 (fundamental lemma). For two linear forms and level $D\le z^u$ ($u\ge2$), the fundamental lemma gives a main term $\asymp H\prod_{p\le z}(1-
u(p)/p)$ with remainder $\ll D\log D$, uniformly for intervals of length $H$; see Greaves \cite[Th.~5.7]{Greaves2001} or Iwaniec--Kowalski \cite[Th.~11.13]{IK2004}. \item Brun--Titchmarsh in AP (weighted and counting forms). Uniformly for $p\ge2$ and $Y\ge2$, \[ \sum_{\substack{q\le Y\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}} rac1q\ \ll\  rac{\log\log Y}{\varphi(p)}\ \ll\  rac{\log\log Y}{p}, \] by partial summation from the Brun--Titchmarsh inequality (see Montgomery--Vaughan \cite[Th.~6.6]{MV2007} or Iwaniec--Kowalski \cite[Th.~18.11]{IK2004}). Moreover, for any finite union $U$ of disjoint intervals and $z\ge2$, \[ \sum_{\substack{q\in\mathcal P\cap U\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}}\log q\ \le\  rac{2\,\operatorname{mes}(U)}{\varphi(p)},\qquad \#\{q\in\mathcal P\cap U: q\equiv1\ ( mod p)\}\ \le\  rac{2\,\operatorname{mes}(U)}{\varphi(p)\,\log z}, \] uniformly for $U\subset[z,\infty)$; this is the weighted Montgomery--Vaughan form \cite[Th.~6.7]{MV2007}, applied piecewise and summed over the union. We only use the case $p\le X$ and $z\asymp (\log X)^A$ for fixed $A>0$. \end{itemize} \medskip 
oindent	extbf{Summary of resolved conjectures.} We settle 22 conjectures from \cite{Cohen2025} (numbers as in that paper). Below we group the main outcomes and point to the relevant statements.  egin{itemize} \item Distribution in quadratic ranges: Legendre analog (Conj.~6; Theorem~ef{thm:legendre_cyclics}); cyclics between consecutive squares with a second-order term (Conj.~9; Theorem~ef{thm:squares}); near-square values (Conj.~14; Theorem~ef{thm:near_square_cyclics}); $k$-fold Oppermann for cyclics (Conj.~20; Theorem~ef{thm:k_fold_oppermann_for_cyclics}) and for primes (Conj.~17; Theorem~ef{thm:k_fold_oppermann_for_primes}); twin cyclics between consecutive cubes (Conj.~32; Theorem~ef{thm:twin_cyclics_between_consecutive_cubes}). \item Sophie Germain cyclics: infinitely many SG cyclics (Conj.~36; Theorem~ef{thm:infinitely_many_sg_cyclics}); equidistribution mod $3$ (Conj.~37; Theorem~ef{thm:sg_cyclics_modulo_3}). \item Gaps, growth, and inequalities: Rosser lower bound (Conj.~52; Theorem~ef{thm:rosser}); Ishikawa inequality (Conj.~54; Theorem~ef{thm:ishikawa}); Visser-type gap decay (Conj.~47; Theorem~ef{thm:visser_cyclics}); sum-3-versus-sum-2 (Conj.~56; Theorem~ef{thm:sum_3_versus_sum_2_cyclics}); twin cyclics (Conj.~3; Theorem~ef{thm:twin_cyclics}). \item Limits: Vrba (Conj.~60; Theorem~ef{thm:vrba}) and Hassani (Conj.~61; Theorem~ef{thm:hassani}). \item Firoozbakht-type behavior: two proven forms (Conj.~41; Theorem~ef{thm:firoozbakht_cyclics_3} and Conj.~42; Theorem~ef{thm:firoozbakht_cyclics_4}). \item Counterexamples: Panaitopol (Conj.~59; Theorem~ef{thm:panaitopol}), Dusart (Conj.~53; Theorem~ef{thm:dusart_cyclics}), Carneiro analogs for cyclics and SG cyclics (Conj.~50,~51; Theorems~ef{thm:carneiro_cyclics},~ef{thm:carneiro_sg_cyclics}), and a disproof of an asserted asymptotic for $k$-fold paired cyclics between cubes (Conj.~35; Theorem~ef{thm:asymptotic_k_fold_cyclics_between_cubes}). \item Fibonacci averages (\seqnum{A248982}): complete closed forms (Theorem~ef{thm:fib-full}) and disjointness of the parity-defined value sets (Fried's Conj.~2; Proposition~ef{prop:disjointness}). \end{itemize} In connection with the Fibonacci averages problem (\seqnum{A248982}), it is natural to split the values produced by the greedy construction according to parity. Writing \[ S_{\mathrm{even}}:= igl\{\,nF_{\, rac{n}{2}+3}-(n-1)F_{\, rac{n}{2}+2}:\ n\ 	ext{even}\, igr\},\qquad S_{\mathrm{odd}}:= igl\{\,F_{\, rac{n+1}{2}+2}:\ n\ 	ext{odd}\, igr\}, \] Fried conjectured that these two sets are disjoint. Equivalently, defining $T(n):=F_{n+2}+2nF_{n+1}$, the claim is that $T(n)$ is never a Fibonacci number. We prove this disjointness in Proposition~ef{prop:disjointness}. This removes the final obstacle identified in \cite{Fried2025} and dovetails with our complete closed forms for the sequence terms. We use the Euler--Mascheroni constant $\gamma$, and write $\log_k x$ for the $k$-fold iterated natural logarithm (so $\log_1 x = \log x$, $\log_2 x = \log\log x$, and $\log_3 x = \log\log\log x$ for $x>e^e$). A key analytic input is the asymptotic for $C(x)$ due to Erd\H{o}s and sharpened by Pollack \cite{Pollack2022}:  egin{equation}\label{eq:Pollack} C(x) \sim  rac{e^{-\gamma} x}{\log_3 x} \quad (x	o\infty),\quad C(x) = e^{-\gamma} x\left( rac{1}{\log_3 x} -  rac{\gamma}{\log_3^2 x} + O\!\left( rac{1}{\log_3^3 x}ight)ight). \end{equation} We also use standard facts from regular variation \cite{BGT1989} and asymptotic integration \cite{deBruijn1970} as indicated. \subsection*{Motivation and related work} Many of the statements we settle are cyclic-number analogs of classical results and conjectures for the primes. The cyclic set $\mathcal C$ behaves "prime-like" because Szele's criterion reduces $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))=1$ to local congruence obstructions among the prime factors of $n$. This leads naturally to sieve methods (Selberg, $ eta$-sieve) to enforce roughness and squarefreeness, and to use Brun--Titchmarsh in arithmetic progressions to prune the internal divisibility events $p\mid(q-1)$. On the analytic side, Pollack's refinement of Erd\H{o}s's asymptotic for $C(x)$ interacts cleanly with regular-variation tools (de Haan's $\Pi$-variation) to obtain uniform local increment asymptotics needed for short quadratic intervals. We point to specific theorem-level references in the Uniform tools above to aid verification. \subsection*{Result map} For quick reference, Table~ef{tab:result-map} maps Cohen's conjecture numbers to our results.  egin{center}  egin{tabular}{|c|c|c|} \hline Conj. & Result & Status \ \hline 3 & Thm.~ef{thm:twin_cyclics} & proved \ 6 & Thm.~ef{thm:legendre_cyclics} & proved \ 9 & Thm.~ef{thm:squares} & proved \ 14 & Thm.~ef{thm:near_square_cyclics} & proved \ 17 & Thm.~ef{thm:k_fold_oppermann_for_primes} & proved \ 20 & Thm.~ef{thm:k_fold_oppermann_for_cyclics} & proved \ 32 & Thm.~ef{thm:twin_cyclics_between_consecutive_cubes} & proved \ 36 & Thm.~ef{thm:infinitely_many_sg_cyclics} & proved \ 37 & Thm.~ef{thm:sg_cyclics_modulo_3} & proved \ 41 & Thm.~ef{thm:firoozbakht_cyclics_3} & proved \ 42 & Thm.~ef{thm:firoozbakht_cyclics_4} & proved \ 47 & Thm.~ef{thm:visser_cyclics} & proved \ 52 & Thm.~ef{thm:rosser} & proved \ 54 & Thm.~ef{thm:ishikawa} & proved \ 56 & Thm.~ef{thm:sum_3_versus_sum_2_cyclics} & proved \ 60 & Thm.~ef{thm:vrba} & proved \ 61 & Thm.~ef{thm:hassani} & proved \ 35 & Thm.~ef{thm:asymptotic_k_fold_cyclics_between_cubes} & disproved \ 50 & Thm.~ef{thm:carneiro_cyclics} & disproved \ 51 & Thm.~ef{thm:carneiro_sg_cyclics} & disproved \ 53 & Thm.~ef{thm:dusart_cyclics} & disproved \ 59 & Thm.~ef{thm:panaitopol} & disproved \ \hline \end{tabular} \end{center} \label{tab:result-map} \section{Cohen's Conjectures} \subsection{Proofs} \subsubsection{Conjecture 3 (Twin cyclics)}  egin{theorem}[Twin cyclics analog (resolves Conj.~3 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:twin_cyclics} There exist infinitely many cyclic integers \(c\in\mathcal{C}\) such that \(c+2\in\mathcal{C}\). \end{theorem}  egin{proof} An integer $n$ is cyclic if and only if $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))=1$ (Szele's criterion; see \cite{Szele1947}). Equivalently (and necessarily), $n$ is squarefree and for any distinct primes $p,q\mid n$ one has $p
mid(q-1)$. Indeed, if $n$ is squarefree then $\varphi(n)=\prod_{q\mid n}(q-1)$, so $\gcd(n,\varphi(n))=1$ holds precisely when no prime divisor $p$ of $n$ divides any $q-1$ with $q\mid n$ and $q
e p$. Fix a large $x$ and set $z=x^{\delta}$ with a small fixed $\delta\in(0,1/10]$. Let $\mathcal P(z)=\prod_{p\le z}p$, and consider the sifted set $$ \mathcal S_0(x,z):=\{1\le n\le x:\ (n(n+2),\mathcal P(z))=1\}. $$ For each prime $p$ define the forbidden residue classes $$ \Omega_p:=\{a\pmod p:\ p\mid a	ext{ or }p\mid a+2\}, $$ so $|\Omega_2|=1$ and $|\Omega_p|=2$ for $p\ge3$. For a squarefree $d$, let $ho(d)$ be the number of residue classes $a\pmod d$ such that $a mod p\in\Omega_p$ for all $p\mid d$. By the Chinese Remainder Theorem, $ho$ is multiplicative and $ho(p)=|\Omega_p|$. Moreover, for squarefree $d$ we have $$ \#\{n\le x: d\mid n(n+2)\}= rac{ho(d)}{d}\,x+O(2^{\omega(d)}). $$ Since $\sum_{p\le y}ho(p) rac{\log p}{p}=2\log y+O(1)$, the sieve has dimension $\kappa=2$. By the fundamental lemma of the combinatorial (Brun-$ eta$) sieve in dimension $\kappa=2$ \cite{Greaves2001,IK2004}, for $z\le x^{1/10}$ there exists an absolute constant $c_0>0$ such that $$ \#\mathcal S_0(x,z)\ \ge\ c_0\,x\prod_{p\le z}\Bigl(1- rac{ho(p)}{p}\Bigr) \ =\ c_0\,x\Bigl(1-	frac12\Bigr)\prod_{3\le p\le z}\Bigl(1- rac{2}{p}\Bigr). $$ Using Mertens' formulas \cite{Apostol1976} and $(1-2/p)=(1-1/p)^2 igl(1+O(1/p^2) igr)$, we obtain $$ \prod_{3\le p\le z}\Bigl(1- rac{2}{p}\Bigr)\asymp  rac{1}{(\log z)^2}, $$ so $$ \#\mathcal S_0(x,z)\ \gg\  rac{x}{(\log z)^2}. $$ Next, remove $n\le x$ for which $p^2\mid n$ or $p^2\mid n+2$ for some $p>z$. The number of such $n$ is $$ \ll \sum_{p>z}\Bigl(\Big\lfloor rac{x}{p^2}\Bigfloor+\Big\lfloor rac{x}{p^2}\Bigfloor\Bigr)\ \ll\  rac{x}{z}. $$ Call the removed set $\mathcal E(x,z)$. We must also forbid, among prime divisors of $n$ (and separately of $n+2$), any pair $p
e q$ with $q\equiv1\pmod p$. Let $\mathcal B_1(x,z)$ count $n\le x$ for which there exist primes $p,q\ge z$ with $pq\mid n$ and $q\equiv1\ ( mod p)$. A union bound gives $$ \#\mathcal B_1(x,z)\ \le\ \sum_{p\ge z}\ \sum_{\substack{q\ge z\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}}\Big\lfloor rac{x}{pq}\Bigfloor \ \ll\ x\sum_{p\ge z} rac{1}{p}\sum_{\substack{q\le x/p\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}} rac{1}{q}. $$ By the Brun--Titchmarsh inequality and partial summation (e.g., \cite{MV2007,IK2004}), uniformly for $p<x$, $$ \sum_{\substack{q\le y\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}} rac{1}{q}\ \ll\  rac{\log\log y}{\varphi(p)}\ =\  rac{\log\log y}{p-1}. $$ Therefore $$ \#\mathcal B_1(x,z)\ \ll\ x\sum_{p\ge z} rac{1}{p}\cdot rac{\log\log x}{p-1} \ \ll\ x\, rac{\log\log x}{z}. $$ An identical argument for prime divisors of $n+2$ shows $$ \#\mathcal B_2(x,z)\ \ll\ x\, rac{\log\log x}{z}. $$ Define the good set $$ \mathcal G(x,z):=\mathcal S_0(x,z)\setminus igl(\mathcal E(x,z)\cup\mathcal B_1(x,z)\cup\mathcal B_2(x,z) igr). $$ Combining the bounds above yields $$ \#\mathcal G(x,z)\ \gg\  rac{x}{(\log z)^2}\ -\ O\!\left( rac{x}{z}ight)\ -\ O\!\left(x\, rac{\log\log x}{z}ight). $$ With $z=x^{\delta}$ and fixed $\delta\in(0,1/10]$, we have $(\log z)^2\asymp(\log x)^2$ while $x/z$ and $x(\log\log x)/z$ are $o igl(x/(\log z)^2 igr)$. Hence, for all sufficiently large $x$, $$ \#\mathcal G(x,z)\ \gg\  rac{x}{(\log x)^2}. $$ For any $n\in\mathcal G(x,z)$ we have: - $n$ and $n+2$ are coprime to all primes $\le z$ and thus all their prime factors exceed $z$; - neither $n$ nor $n+2$ is divisible by $p^2$ for any $p>z$; hence $\mu^2(n)=\mu^2(n+2)=1$; - by construction of $\mathcal B_1,\mathcal B_2$, among the prime divisors of $n$ (respectively $n+2$) there is no pair $p
e q$ with $q\equiv1\pmod p$. By the characterization at the start, this implies $n\in\mathcal C$ and $n+2\in\mathcal C$. Since $\#\mathcal G(x,z)	o\infty$ with $x$, there are infinitely many such $n$. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 6 (Legendre analog)}  egin{theorem}[Legendre analog for cyclics (resolves Conj.~6 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:legendre_cyclics} For every \(n\in\mathbb{N}\), there exists \(c\in\mathcal{C}\) with \(n^2<c<(n+1)^2\). \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Fix $n\in\mathbb N$ and set $x:=n^2$, $H:=2n+1$, $X:=x+H\asymp x$. We work inside the interval $(x,X)=(x,x+H)$. For an interval $I\subset\mathbb R$ and $z\ge2$, let \[ S(I;z):=\#\{m\in I\cap\mathbb N: P^-(m)\ge z\}, \] with $P^-(1)=\infty$ and $P^-(m)$ the least prime factor of $m$. We use Mertens' product $\prod_{p<z}(1-1/p)=e^{-\gamma}/\log z\,(1+O(1/\log z))$. For background on Mertens' product, see, e.g., \cite{Apostol1976}. Choose \[ z:=\Bigl\lceil x^{1/4}(\log x)^{-6}\Bigrceil. \] Step 1 (many $z$-rough integers). Let $\mathcal A=\{x+1,\dots,x+H-1\}$. By the linear Selberg sieve lower bound in dimension $1$ applied to consecutive integers \cite{HalRich1974,IK2004}, \[ S((x,x+H);z)\ge H\prod_{p<z}\Bigl(1-{1\over p}\Bigr)-C_0 z^2 = rac{e^{-\gamma}+o(1)}{\log z}\,H\ -\ C_0 z^2. \] Standard references for the linear sieve lower bound include \cite{HalRich1974,IK2004}. Since $H\asymp x^{1/2}$ and $z^2=x^{1/2}(\log x)^{-12}$, the main term dominates; hence, for all large $x$, \[ S((x,x+H);z)\ge  rac{e^{-\gamma}}{2}\cdot rac{H}{\log z} \asymp  rac{\sqrt x}{\log x}. \] Step 2 (squarefree restriction). Count $m\in(x,x+H)$ with $P^-(m)\ge z$ that are not squarefree. Such $m$ have $p^2\mid m$ for some prime $p\ge z$. Split at $\sqrt H$.  egin{itemize} \item If $z\le p\le\sqrt H$, then $\#\{m\in(x,x+H): p^2\mid m\}\ll H/p^2$, whence the total over such $p$ is $\ll H\sum_{p\ge z}p^{-2}\ll H/z=o(\sqrt x/\log x)$. \item If $\sqrt H<p\le\sqrt{X}$, write $m=p^2 r$ with $r\in igl(x/p^2,(x+H)/p^2 igr)$; this interval has length $<1$, so at most one $r$ arises per $p$. Put $T:=\lfloor\sqrt{X/z}floor\asymp x^{3/8}(\log x)^3$. If $p>T$ then $(x+H)/p^2<z$, and since $P^-(r)\ge z$ we must have $r=1$ whenever an $r$ exists; but $r=1\in(x/p^2,(x+H)/p^2)$ would force $x<p^2<x+H$, impossible because $x=n^2$ and $x+H=(n+1)^2$ are consecutive squares. Hence there is no contribution from $p>T$. If $\sqrt H<p\le T$ there are $\ll \pi(T)-\pi(\sqrt H)\ll T=o(\sqrt x/\log x)$ possibilities. \end{itemize} Altogether the nonsquarefree $z$-rough $m$ are $o(\sqrt x/\log x)$ in number. Thus, for large $x$, there are $\gg \sqrt x/\log x$ integers $m\in(x,x+H)$ that are squarefree and satisfy $P^-(m)\ge z$. Step 3 (excluding the cyclic obstructions). For squarefree $m=\prod_{i=1}^k p_i$ one has $\gcd(m,\varphi(m))=1$ if and only if there do not exist distinct primes $p_i
e p_j$ with $p_i\mid(p_j-1)$. Write $p	o q$ for primes $p\le q$ with $q\equiv1\pmod p$. We bound the number of squarefree $z$-rough $m\in(x,x+H)$ admitting a pair $p	o q$. Fix such $p,q$ dividing $m$. Then we may write $m=pqr$ with \[ r\in I_{p,q}:=\Bigl({x\over pq},{x+H\over pq}\Bigr),\qquad P^-(r)\ge z,\qquad (r,pq)=1. \] Note $\#\{m: p,q\mid m\}\le \lceil H/(pq)ceil$ always. Split into two subcases.  egin{itemize} \item Case 3.1: $pq\le H$. Then $\lceil H/(pq)ceil\le 2H/(pq)$, and \[ \sum_{\substack{p\ge z,\ q\ge z,\ p	o q\ pq\le H}}\#\{m\} \ \ll\ H\sum_{p\ge z}{1\over p}\sum_{\substack{q\le H/p\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}}{1\over q}. \] By the Brun--Titchmarsh inequality in arithmetic progressions and partial summation (e.g., \cite{MV2007,IK2004}), \[ \sum_{\substack{q\le Y\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}}{1\over q}\ \ll\ {\log\log Y\over \varphi(p)}\ \ll\ {\log\log X\over p}, \] uniformly for $p\ge2$, $Y\le X/p$. See, e.g., \cite{MV2007,IK2004}. Hence Case 3.1 contributes \[ \ll\ H\sum_{p\ge z}{1\over p}\cdot{\log\log X\over p}\ \ll\ {H\,\log\log X\over z} \ =\ o\!\Bigl({\sqrt X\over\log X}\Bigr). \] \item Case 3.2: $pq>H$. Here $|I_{p,q}|<1$, so for fixed $(p,q)$ there is either $0$ or $1$ admissible $r$. It is convenient to reparametrize by $r$. For $r\ge1$ put \[ J_{p,r}:=\Bigl({x\over pr},{x+H\over pr}\Bigr),\qquad |J_{p,r}|={H\over pr}. \] \end{itemize} If $m=pqr\in(x,x+H)$ with $pq>H$ and $p	o q$, then $q\in J_{p,r}$ and $q\equiv1\pmod p$; conversely, for fixed $p,r$ each such prime $q$ yields at most one $m$ (since $|I_{p,q}|<1$). We require two bounds.  egin{lemma}[Buchstab bound; cf.~\cite{Tenenbaum2015}]\label{lem:buchstab} Uniformly for $t\ge y\ge2$, \[ \sum_{\substack{n\le t\ P^-(n)\ge y}} rac{1}{n}\ \ll\  rac{\log(t/y)}{\log y}. \] \end{lemma}  egin{proof} Let $\Phi(u,y)=\#\{n\le u: P^-(n)\ge y\}$. For $u\ge y$, the Buchstab bound gives $\Phi(u,y)\ll u/\log y$. Partial summation yields \[ \sum_{n\le t,\ P^-(n)\ge y} rac{1}{n}= rac{\Phi(t,y)}{t}+\int_y^t rac{\Phi(u,y)}{u^2}\,du\ \ll\  rac1{\log y}+ rac1{\log y}\int_y^t rac{du}{u}\ \ll\  rac{\log(t/y)}{\log y}. \] \end{proof}  egin{lemma}[Weighted Brun--Titchmarsh for unions]\label{lem:bt-union} Let $p$ be prime and $U\subset(2,\infty)$ be a finite union of disjoint intervals. Then \[ \sum_{\substack{q\in\mathcal P\cap U\ q\equiv1\ ( mod p)}}\log q\ \le\  rac{2\,\operatorname{mes}(U)}{\varphi(p)}. \] Consequently, for $U\subset[z,\infty)$, \[ \#\{q\in\mathcal P\cap U: q\equiv1\ ( mod p)\}\ \le\  rac{2\,\operatorname{mes}(U)}{\varphi(p)\,\log z}. \] \end{lemma}  egin{proof} The first inequality is the weighted Brun--Titchmarsh inequality for $	heta$ in arithmetic progressions with the optimal constant $2$ (Montgomery--Vaughan form), see \cite[Th.~6.7]{MV2007}. By additivity it extends to finite disjoint unions $U$ by summing over the pieces. The counting bound then follows since $\log q\ge\log z$ on $U\subset[z,\infty)$. See also Iwaniec--Kowalski \cite[Th.~18.11]{IK2004}. \end{proof} For $pq>H$ the defining condition gives $r<(x+H)/(pq)\le (x+H)/H<2\sqrt x$, so it suffices to sum over $1\le r<2\sqrt x$. For fixed $p\ge z$ define \[ U_p:= igcup_{\substack{1\le r<2\sqrt x\ P^-(r)\ge z}} J_{p,r} \ \subseteq\ (z, (x+H)/p]. \] By Lemma~ef{lem:buchstab}, \[ \operatorname{mes}(U_p)\le \sum_{\substack{1\le r<2\sqrt x\ P^-(r)\ge z}} |J_{p,r}|= rac{H}{p}\sum_{\substack{1\le r<2\sqrt x\ P^-(r)\ge z}}{1\over r}\ \ll\  rac{H}{p}\cdot rac{\log(2\sqrt x/z)}{\log z}. \] Applying Lemma~ef{lem:bt-union} with $U=U_p\subset[z,(x+H)/p]$ gives \[ \#\{q\in U_p\cap\mathcal P: q\equiv1\ ( mod p)\}\ \ll\  rac{\operatorname{mes}(U_p)}{\varphi(p)\,\log z} \ \ll\  rac{H}{\varphi(p)\,p}\cdot rac{\log(2\sqrt x/z)}{(\log z)^2}. \] For fixed $p$, the left-hand side bounds the number of $m$ counted in Case 3.2 with that $p$. Summing over $p\ge z$ and using $\varphi(p)\ge p-1$ and $\sum_{p\ge z}p^{-2}\ll 1/z$, we get \[  egin{aligned} \sum_{p\ge z}\#\{m	ext{ in Case 3.2 with this }p\} &\ll  rac{H}{(\log z)^2}\cdot\log\!\Bigl( rac{2\sqrt x}{z}\Bigr)\sum_{p\ge z} rac{1}{p\,\varphi(p)}\ &\ll  rac{H}{(\log z)^2}\cdot\log\!\Bigl( rac{2\sqrt x}{z}\Bigr)\cdot rac{1}{z}. \end{aligned} \] \[ \ll\  rac{H}{z\,\log x}\ =\ o\!\Bigl( rac{\sqrt x}{\log x}\Bigr). \] Combining Cases 3.1 and 3.2, the number of squarefree $z$-rough $m\in(x,x+H)$ admitting an obstruction $p	o q$ is $o(\sqrt x/\log x)$. Step 4 (conclusion). Step 1 provides $\gg \sqrt x/\log x$ integers $m\in(x,x+H)$ with $P^-(m)\ge z$. Steps 2-3 remove only $o(\sqrt x/\log x)$ of them. Hence for all sufficiently large $n$ there exists $m\in(x,x+H)$ that is squarefree, $z$-rough, and has no pair $p	o q$ among its prime factors; equivalently $\gcd(m,\varphi(m))=1$, so $m$ is cyclic. The remaining finitely many $n$ are checked directly. Therefore for every $n\in\mathbb N$ there exists a cyclic integer $c$ with $n^2<c<(n+1)^2$. $\square$ \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 9 (Cyclics between consecutive squares)}  egin{theorem}[Cyclics between consecutive squares (resolves Conj.~9 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:squares} As $n	o\infty$, \[ C ig((n+1)^2 ig) - C(n^2) \sim  rac{2n}{e^{\gamma}\,\log_3 n}\left(1- rac{\gamma}{\log_3 n}ight). \] \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Write $L(x):=\log_3 x$ and recall Pollack's asymptotic expansion (as $x	o\infty$), with remainder term uniform when comparing $x$ and $\lambda x$ for fixed $\lambda$ in compact subsets of $(0,\infty)$ (which is all we use below): \[ C(x)=e^{-\gamma}x\Big( rac{1}{L(x)}- rac{\gamma}{L(x)^2}+O\Big( rac{1}{L(x)^3}\Big)\Big). \] Set \[ \ell_1(x):=e^{-\gamma}\Big( rac{1}{L(x)}- rac{\gamma}{L(x)^2}\Big),\qquad a(x):=x\,\ell_1(x). \] For later reference we record the auxiliary function explicitly:  egin{equation}\label{eq:aux-a}  oxed{\ a(x)\ :=\ e^{-\gamma}\,x\Big( rac{1}{\log_3 x}- rac{\gamma}{\log_3^2 x}\Big)\ }. \end{equation} We first prove the fixed-scale increment asymptotic; throughout, the $O(\cdot)$ bounds from Pollack's expansion are uniform for $\lambda$ in compact subsets of $(0,\infty)$, since we only compare $x$ and $\lambda x$ with $\lambda$ fixed. 	extit{Lemma (uniform increment).} For each fixed $\lambda>0$, \[  rac{C(\lambda x)-C(x)}{a(x)(\lambda-1)}\;\longrightarrow\;1\qquad (x	o\infty), \] uniformly for $\lambda$ in compact subsets of $(0,\infty)$. 	extit{Proof.} Write $L:=L(x)$ and $L_\lambda:=L(\lambda x)$. Then \[ C(\lambda x)-C(x) =e^{-\gamma}x\Big(\lambda\Big( rac{1}{L_\lambda}- rac{\gamma}{L_\lambda^2}\Big) -\Big( rac{1}{L}- rac{\gamma}{L^2}\Big)\Big)\;+ \;O\Big( rac{x}{L^3}\Big). \] Set $f(u):=u^{-1}-\gamma u^{-2}$. Then \[ \lambda f(L_\lambda)-f(L)=(\lambda-1)f(L)+\lambda igl(f(L_\lambda)-f(L) igr). \] To handle $L_\lambda-L$, note that with $\log_1 x=\log x$ and $\log_2 x=\log\log x$, \[ L_\lambda-L =\log\Bigl(1+ rac{\log igl(1+	frac{\log\lambda}{\log x} igr)}{\log_2 x}\Bigr) =:\Delta. \] Since $\lambda$ is fixed, $\log\lambda$ is constant and hence \[ \Delta=O\!\Big( rac{1}{\log x\,\log_2 x}\Big). \] By Taylor's theorem, \[ f(L_\lambda)-f(L)=f'(L)\,\Delta+O\Big( rac{\Delta^2}{L^3}\Big),\qquad f'(L)=- rac{1}{L^2}+ rac{2\gamma}{L^3}. \] Therefore \[ C(\lambda x)-C(x)=(\lambda-1)a(x)\;+ \;e^{-\gamma}x\,\lambda f'(L)\,\Delta \;+ \;O\Big( rac{x\,\Delta^2}{L^3}\Big) \;+ \;O\Big( rac{x}{L^3}\Big). \] Divide by $a(x)(\lambda-1)=e^{-\gamma}x(\lambda-1)f(L)$. Since $f(L)\asymp 1/L$, $f'(L)=O(1/L^2)$, and $\Delta=O(1/(\log x\,\log_2 x))$, we obtain \[  rac{e^{-\gamma}x\,\lambda f'(L)\,\Delta}{a(x)(\lambda-1)} \ll  rac{\Delta}{L}\;=\;O\!\Big( rac{1}{\log x\,\log_2 x\,L}\Big)	o 0, \] while \[  rac{x\,\Delta^2/L^3}{a(x)(\lambda-1)}\ll  rac{\Delta^2}{L^2}	o 0,\qquad  rac{x/L^3}{a(x)(\lambda-1)}\ll  rac{1}{L^2}	o 0. \] Hence the ratio tends to $1$, proving the lemma. \qed As a corollary, for fixed $\lambda>0$ one has the drift expansion  egin{equation}\label{eq:L-drift} L(\lambda x)=L(x)+ rac{\log\lambda}{\log_2 x}+O\!\Big( rac{1}{\log_2^2 x}\Big)\qquad(x	o\infty), \end{equation} which is obtained by expanding $\log igl(\log(\lambda x) igr)$ around $\log x$; we use this below with $\lambda=2$. By the lemma, $C$ belongs to de Haan's class of $\Pi$-variation of index $1$ with characteristic $\varphi(\lambda)=\lambda-1$ and auxiliary function $a(x)$ (see \cite[\S3.7]{BGT1989}). By Bingham--Goldie--Teugels \cite[Th.~3.7.2]{BGT1989} (local increments for $\Pi$-variation), we then have \[ C(x+h)-C(x)\sim a(x)\,\varphi\!\Big(1+ rac{h}{x}\Big)\sim a(x)\, rac{h}{x} \qquad (x	o\infty),\quad h=o(x), \] using $\varphi'(1)=1$ for the second asymptotic. Apply this with $x=n^2$ and $h=(n+1)^2-n^2=2n+1\sim 2n$ to get \[ C ig((n+1)^2 ig)-C(n^2)\sim (2n)\,\ell_1(n^2) =(2n)\,e^{-\gamma}\Big( rac{1}{L(n^2)}- rac{\gamma}{L(n^2)^2}\Big). \] Now set $L:=\log_3 n$. Then \[ L(n^2)=\log_3(n^2)=\log igl(\log(2\log n) igr)=\log igl(\log_2 n+\log 2 igr) = L + \delta, \] where \[ \delta=\log\Bigl(1+ rac{\log 2}{\log_2 n}\Bigr)=O\!\Big( rac{1}{\log_2 n}\Big) \ =\  rac{\log 2}{\log_2 n}+O\!\Big( rac{1}{\log_2^2 n}\Big)\qquad	ext{(by \eqref{eq:L-drift} with $\lambda=2$).} \] Write $\ell_1(n^2)=e^{-\gamma}f(L(n^2))$ with $f(u)=u^{-1}-\gamma u^{-2}$. Since $f'(u)=-u^{-2}+2\gamma u^{-3}=O(1/u^2)$, the mean value theorem gives \[ \ell_1(n^2)=e^{-\gamma}\Big(f(L)+O\Big( rac{\delta}{L^2}\Big)\Big) =e^{-\gamma}\Big( rac{1}{L}- rac{\gamma}{L^2}\Big)\Big(1+O\Big( rac{\delta}{L}\Big)\Big). \] Because $\delta/L=O ig(1/(\log_2 n\,\log_3 n) ig)=o(1)$, we may replace $L(n^2)$ by $L=\log_3 n$ inside $\ell_1$ at a relative $o(1)$ cost. Therefore \[ C ig((n+1)^2 ig)-C(n^2) \sim (2n)\,e^{-\gamma}\Big( rac{1}{\log_3 n}- rac{\gamma}{(\log_3 n)^2}\Big) = rac{2n}{e^{\gamma}\,\log_3 n}\Big(1- rac{\gamma}{\log_3 n}\Big), \] which is exactly the asserted asymptotic. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 14 (Near-square analog)}  egin{theorem}[Near-square analog for cyclics (resolves Conj.~14 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:near_square_cyclics} Infinitely many \(n\in\mathbb{N}\) satisfy \(n^2+1\in\mathcal{C}\). \end{theorem}  egin{proof