lfloor\log Xfloor-1$. On each bin, $\log(X/p)\asymp j$, so $$\sum_{X/e^{j+1}<p\le X/e^{j}}  rac{1}{p\,\log(X/p)}\ll  rac{1}{j}\sum_{X/e^{j+1}<p\le X/e^{j}} rac{1}{p} \ll  rac{1}{j}\Bigl(\log\log rac{X}{e^{j}}-\log\log rac{X}{e^{j+1}}+O\!\Bigl( rac{1}{\log X}\Bigr)\Bigr).$$  egin{flushleft} Summing over $j$ and using the telescoping together with $\sum_{j\le \log X}  rac{1}{j(\log X-j)}\ll (\log\log X)/(\log X)$, $$\sum_{p\le X/e} rac{1}{p\,\log(X/p)}\ll  rac{\log\log X}{\log X}.$$ \end{flushleft} Hence $$T_1\ll X\cdot rac{\log\log X}{\log X}.$$ For $T_2$, note that $p>X/e$ implies $\lfloor X/pfloor\le e$. Since $\pi(X;p,1)\le \lfloor X/pfloor$, we get $$T_2\le \sum_{X/e<p\le X}\Bigl\lfloor rac{X}{p}\Bigrfloor\le \sum_{k=1}^{\lfloor efloor}\!k\, igl(\pi(X/k)-\pi(X/(k+1)) igr)\ll \sum_{k=1}^{\lfloor efloor}\! rac{X/k}{\log(X/k)}\ll  rac{X}{\log X}.$$ Combining the two ranges, $$S_2=T_1+T_2\ll X rac{\log\log X}{\log X}=o\!\left( rac{X}{(\log y)^2}ight)\quad	ext{since }(\log y)^2=\log\log X.$$ Thus $\#\mathcal B_{2n+1}=o igl(x/(\log y)^2 igr)$. \medskip 
oindent	extit{Lemma (aggregated parameters).} With $y=\exp\sqrt{\log\log x}$ one has, for some absolute $c_0>0$ and all sufficiently large $x$, \[ \#\mathcal S_0(x,y)\ \ge\ c_0\, rac{x}{(\log y)^2},\qquad \#\mathcal S_1(x,y)\ \ll\  rac{x}{y}+ rac{\sqrt{x}}{\log x}\ =\ o\!\left( rac{x}{(\log y)^2}ight), \] and \[ \#\mathcal B_n\ \ll\ x\, rac{\log\log x}{y}\ =\ o\!\left( rac{x}{(\log y)^2}ight),\qquad \#\mathcal B_{2n+1}\ \ll\ x\, rac{\log\log x}{\log x}\ =\ o\!\left( rac{x}{(\log y)^2}ight). \] In particular, $\#\mathcal G(x)\gg x/(\log y)^2\asymp x/\log\log x$. 
oindent	extit{Proof.} Combine the bounds proved in Steps 1--4 and note that $(\log y)^2=\log\log x$. Step 5 (conclusion). Set $$\mathcal G(x):=\mathcal S_0(x,y)\setminus igl(\mathcal S_1(x,y)\cup\mathcal B_n\cup\mathcal B_{2n+1} igr).$$ By Steps 1--4 and the lemma, $$\#\mathcal G(x)\ge \#\mathcal S_0(x,y)-\#\mathcal S_1(x,y)-\#\mathcal B_n-\#\mathcal B_{2n+1}\gg  rac{x}{(\log y)^2}\asymp  rac{x}{\log\log x}.$$ For each $n\in\mathcal G(x)$, all prime divisors of $n$ and of $2n+1$ exceed $y$, these integers are squarefree, and there is no pair of distinct primes $p,q$ dividing $n$ (respectively $2n+1$) with $p\mid(q-1)$. By Szele's characterization, both $n$ and $2n+1$ are cyclic. Hence every $n\in\mathcal G(x)$ is a Sophie Germain cyclic. It follows that, for all sufficiently large $x$, $$C_{\mathrm{SG}}(x)\ge \#\mathcal G(x)\gg  rac{x}{\log\log x},$$ so there are infinitely many Sophie Germain cyclics. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 37 (SG cyclics modulo 3)}  egin{theorem}[SG cyclics modulo 3 (resolves Conj.~37 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:sg_cyclics_modulo_3} As the number of SG cyclics grows, the limiting fractions congruent to 1 and 3 mod 3 are equal. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} \[N_r(x):=\#\{n\le x:\, n\in S,\ n\equiv r\pmod 3\},\qquad C_{\mathrm{SG}}(x):=\#\{n\le x:\, n\in S\}. \] Then $$\lim_{x	o\infty} rac{N_1(x)-N_0(x)}{C_{\mathrm{SG}}(x)}=0.$$ Equivalently, among SG cyclics the limiting fractions in the classes $1$ and $3\pmod3$ are equal. Write $L_1(n)=n$ and $L_2(n)=2n+1$. For a positive integer $m$, the condition $\gcd(m,\varphi(m))=1$ is equivalent to: (i) $m$ is squarefree, and (ii) there is no pair of distinct prime divisors $p,q\mid m$ with $p\mid(q-1)$ (cf. Szele \cite{Szele1947}). Indeed, $p^2\mid m\Rightarrow p\mid\varphi(m)$, and if $p,q\mid m$ with $p\mid(q-1)$ then also $p\mid\varphi(m)=\prod_{r\mid m}(r-1)$; conversely, if $m$ is squarefree and no such pair occurs then $\gcd igl(m,\prod_{q\mid m}(q-1) igr)=1$. Fix large $x$ and set $y:=\lfloor\log xfloor\ge3$. We split small primes ($\le y$) from large primes ($>y$). 1) Lower bound for $C_{\mathrm{SG}}(x)$. Let $\mathcal P(y)=\prod_{p\le y}p$ and $$\mathcal T(y):=\Bigl\{n\le x:\, \gcd igl(L_1(n)L_2(n),\mathcal P(y) igr)=1\Bigr\}.$$ For each prime $p$, the set of residues $n\pmod p$ with $p\mid L_1(n)L_2(n)$ has cardinality $
u(p)$, where $
u(2)=1$ and $
u(p)=2$ for $p\ge3$. By the two-dimensional Brun--Selberg sieve (fundamental lemma; see \cite{HalRich1974,Greaves2001,IK2004}), $$\#\mathcal T(y)\asymp x\prod_{p\le y}\Bigl(1- rac{
u(p)}{p}\Bigr)=\Bigl(1-	frac12\Bigr)x\prod_{3\le p\le y}\Bigl(1- rac{2}{p}\Bigr)\asymp  rac{x}{(\log y)^2}.	ag{1}$$ Remove from $\mathcal T(y)$ those $n$ that still violate cyclicity for $L_1$ or $L_2$ at large primes ($>y$). - Large square divisors: for $j\in\{1,2\}$ the number of $n\le x$ with $p^2\mid L_j(n)$ for some prime $p>y$ is bounded by \[\sum_{y<p\le\sqrt{2x+1}}\Bigl( rac{x}{p^2}+1\Bigr)\ \ll\ x\sum_{p>y} rac{1}{p^2}\ +\ \pi(\sqrt{2x+1})\ \ll\  rac{x}{y}\ +\  rac{\sqrt{x}}{\log x}.	ag{2}\] - Large-large pair violations in one $L_j$: existence of primes $y<p<q\le 2x+1$ with $p\mid L_j(n)$, $q\mid L_j(n)$ and $q\equiv1\pmod p$. For each fixed pair $(p,q)$ there is exactly one residue class $ mod\,pq$ for $n$ (by CRT), hence the count per pair is $ rac{x}{pq}+O(1)$. Summing over pairs we get, for each $j$, a contribution \[\Sigma_j\ \le\ x\sum_{\substack{y<p<q\le 2x+1\ q\equiv1\ (p)}} rac{1}{pq}\ +\ \sum_{\substack{y<p<q\le 2x+1\ q\equiv1\ (p)}}1\ =:\ x\,S_1\ +\ S_2.\] We bound $S_1$ and $S_2$ separately. * Bound for $S_1$. By the Brun--Titchmarsh inequality and partial summation (e.g., \cite{MV2007,IK2004}), for $t>p$ we have $$\sum_{\substack{q\le t\ q\equiv1\ (p)}} rac{1}{q}\ \ll\  rac{1}{\varphi(p)}\log\log t\ \ll\  rac{\log\log t}{p-1}.$$ Therefore $$S_1\le \sum_{p>y} rac{1}{p}\sum_{\substack{y<q\le 2x+1\ q\equiv1\ (p)}} rac{1}{q}\ \ll\ \log\log x\sum_{p>y} rac{1}{p(p-1)}\ \ll\  rac{\log\log x}{y}.	ag{3}$$ * Bound for $S_2$. Write $U:=2x+1$. Split at $\sqrt U$: \[S_2=\sum_{\substack{y<p\le\sqrt U}}\pi(U;p,1)\ +\ \sum_{\substack{\sqrt U<p\le U}}\pi(U;p,1)=:S_{2,\le}+S_{2,>}. \] For $p\le\sqrt U$, the Brun--Titchmarsh inequality gives (e.g., \cite{MV2007,IK2004}) $$\pi(U;p,1)\ \le\  rac{2U}{\varphi(p)\log(U/p)}\ \le\  rac{4U}{(p-1)\log U},$$ whence $$S_{2,\le}\ \ll\  rac{U}{\log U}\sum_{p>y} rac{1}{p-1}\ \ll\  rac{U}{\log U}\sum_{p>y} rac{1}{p}\ \ll\  rac{U\log\log U}{\log U}.	ag{4}$$ For $p>\sqrt U$, any prime $q\le U$ with $q\equiv1\pmod p$ forces $p\mid(q-1)$ and $p>\sqrt{q-1}$, so $p$ is the unique prime factor of $q-1$ exceeding $\sqrt{q-1}$. Thus each prime $q\le U$ contributes to at most one such $p$, and $$S_{2,>}\ \le\ \pi(U)\ \ll\  rac{U}{\log U}.	ag{5}$$ Combining (4)-(5), $$S_2\ \ll\  rac{U\log\log U}{\log U}\ =\  rac{x\log\log x}{\log x}.	ag{6}$$ From (3) and (6), for each $j\in\{1,2\}$, $$\Sigma_j\ \ll\ x\cdot rac{\log\log x}{y}\ +\  rac{x\log\log x}{\log x}.	ag{7}$$ Let $\mathcal T^{m good}(y)$ be the subset of $\mathcal T(y)$ that suffers neither large squares (in (2)) nor large-large pair violations (in (7)) for $L_1$ and $L_2$. Using (1)-(2)-(7), \[\#\mathcal T^{m good}(y)\ \ge\ \#\mathcal T(y)\ -\ O\!\Bigl( rac{x}{y}+ rac{\sqrt{x}}{\log x}+x rac{\log\log x}{y}+ rac{x\log\log x}{\log x}\Bigr).	ag{8}\] Taking $y=\lfloor\log xfloor$, (1) yields $\#\mathcal T(y)\asymp x/(\log\log x)^2$, while every error term on the right of (8) is $o igl(x/(\log\log x)^2 igr)$. Hence $$\#\mathcal T^{m good}(y)\ \gg\  rac{x}{(\log\log x)^2}.	ag{9}$$ Each $n\in\mathcal T^{m good}(y)$ has both $L_1(n)$ and $L_2(n)$ squarefree with all prime factors $>y$ and, within each $L_j$, no pair $p,q\mid L_j(n)$ with $p\mid(q-1)$. Thus both $L_1(n)$ and $L_2(n)$ are cyclic, so $$C_{\mathrm{SG}}(x)=\#S\ \ge\ \#\mathcal T^{m good}(y)\ \gg\  rac{x}{(\log\log x)^2}.	ag{10}$$ 2) Upper bound for $N_0(x)+N_1(x)$. Note $$n\equiv0\ (3)\iff 3\mid L_1(n),\qquad n\equiv1\ (3)\iff 3\mid L_2(n).$$ If $3\mid L_j(n)$ and $n\in S$, then no prime $q\equiv1\pmod3$ divides $L_j(n)$ (else $(3,q)$ violates cyclicity of $L_j(n)$). Let $$Q:=\{\,q:\ y<q\le 2x+1,\ q\equiv1\ (3),\ q	ext{ prime}\,\}.$$ For $j\in\{1,2\}$ and $a_1=0$, $a_2=1$, define $$S_j(x;y):=\#\Bigl\{n\le x:\ n\equiv a_j\ (3),\ q
mid L_j(n)\  orall\ q\in Q\Bigr\}.$$ Then $$N_0(x)\le S_1(x;y),\qquad N_1(x)\le S_2(x;y),\qquad |N_1(x)-N_0(x)|\le S_1(x;y)+S_2(x;y).	ag{11}$$ Let $\mathcal A_j=\{n\le x:\ n\equiv a_j\ (3)\}$, so $X:=\#\mathcal A_j=x/3+O(1)$. For squarefree $d$ supported on primes in $Q$, the system $d\mid L_j(n)$ together with $n\equiv a_j\ (3)$ picks exactly one residue class modulo $3d$; hence $$A_j(d):=\#\{n\in\mathcal A_j:\ d\mid L_j(n)\}= rac{X}{d}+O(1).	ag{12}$$ Applying the upper-bound Selberg--Brun sieve (see, e.g., \cite{HalRich1974,IK2004}) with sifting set $Q$, level $z=2x+1$, and weights supported on $d\le D=x^{1/2}$, one obtains $$S_j(x;y)\ \le\ X\,V(z)\,F\!\Bigl( rac{\log D}{\log z}\Bigr)+O(D),	ag{13}$$ where $V(z)=\prod_{q\in Q,\ q<z}(1-1/q)=\prod_{q\in Q}(1-1/q)$ and the dimension-$1$ sieve function $F$ is uniformly bounded. Thus $$S_j(x;y)\ \ll\  rac{x}{3}\prod_{q\in Q}\Bigl(1- rac1q\Bigr)+x^{1/2}.	ag{14}$$ By PNT in arithmetic progressions modulo $3$ and partial summation, $$\sum_{\substack{q\le t\ q\equiv1\ (3)}} rac1q=	frac12\log\log t+O(1),\qquad \prod_{\substack{q\le t\ q\equiv1\ (3)}}\Bigl(1- rac1q\Bigr)\asymp (\log t)^{-1/2}.$$ Therefore $$\prod_{q\in Q}\Bigl(1- rac1q\Bigr)= rac{\displaystyle\prod_{\substack{q\le 2x+1\ q\equiv1\ (3)}}(1-1/q)}{\displaystyle\prod_{\substack{q\le y\ q\equiv1\ (3)}}(1-1/q)}\ \ll\ \Bigl( rac{\log y}{\log x}\Bigr)^{1/2}.	ag{15}$$ Combining (11), (14), and (15) with $y=\lfloor\log xfloor$ gives $$|N_1(x)-N_0(x)|\ \le\ S_1(x;y)+S_2(x;y)\ \ll\ x\Bigl( rac{\log\log x}{\log x}\Bigr)^{1/2}+x^{1/2}.	ag{16}$$ 3) Conclusion. From (10) and (16), $$ rac{|N_1(x)-N_0(x)|}{C_{\mathrm{SG}}(x)}\ \ll\  rac{x igl(	frac{\log\log x}{\log x} igr)^{1/2}+x^{1/2}}{x/(\log\log x)^2}\ \ll\  rac{(\log\log x)^{5/2}}{\sqrt{\log x}}+ rac{(\log\log x)^2}{\sqrt{x}}\ 	o\ 0.$$ Thus the limiting fractions of SG cyclics in the residue classes $1$ and $3\pmod3$ are equal. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 41 (Firoozbakht analog 3)}  egin{theorem}[Firoozbakht analog for cyclics 3 (resolves Conj.~41 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:firoozbakht_cyclics_3} For each \(k\) there exists \(N(k)\) such that for all \(n>N(k)\), \(c_n^{1/(n+k)}>c_{n+1}^{1/(n+k+1)}\). \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Let $L(x):=\log_3 x=\log\log\log x$ for $x\ge e^{e^e}$ and let $$C(x):=\#\{m\le x: \gcd(m,\varphi(m))=1\}.$$ By Pollack's refinement of Erdos' asymptotic \cite{Pollack2022}, there exist absolute constants $X_0\ge e^{e^e}$ and $A_0>0$ such that for all $x\ge X_0$, $$ C(x)=e^{-\gamma}x\Bigl( rac1{L(x)}- rac{\gamma}{L(x)^2}+ rac{q}{L(x)^3}+R(x)\Bigr),\qquad q=\gamma^2+ rac{\pi^2}{12},\quad |R(x)|\le  rac{A_0}{L(x)^4}. $$ Define the smooth comparison functions $$ F_\pm(x):=e^{-\gamma}x\Bigl( rac1{L(x)}- rac{\gamma}{L(x)^2}+ rac{q}{L(x)^3}\pm rac{A_0}{L(x)^4}\Bigr)\qquad(x\ge X_0), $$ so that for $x\ge X_0$, $$ F_-(x)\le C(x)\le F_+(x). $$ 1) Uniform lower bound for $F_-'$. Write $\ell:=L(x)$ and $G(\ell):=\ell^{-1}-\gamma\ell^{-2}+q\ell^{-3}-A_0\ell^{-4}$. Since $L'(x)=(x\log x\,\log_2 x)^{-1}$, $$ F_-'(x)=e^{-\gamma}\Bigl[G(\ell)+x\,G'(\ell)L'(x)\Bigr]. $$ Because $G'(\ell)=-\ell^{-2}+O(\ell^{-3})$, there exist $X_1\ge X_0$ and $C_1>0$ such that for all $x\ge X_1$, $$  igl|x\,G'(\ell)L'(x) igr|\le  rac{C_1}{\ell^2\log x\,\log_2 x}. $$ Moreover $G(\ell)=\ell^{-1}+O(\ell^{-2})$. As $\ell	o\infty$ and $\log x\,\log_2 x	o\infty$, enlarging $X_1$ if needed we obtain $$ F_-'(x)\ge e^{-\gamma}\Bigl( rac{1}{2L(x)}\Bigr)\qquad(x\ge X_1).	ag{1} $$ In particular $F_-$ is strictly increasing on $[X_1,\infty)$ and, since $F_-(x)\gg x/L(x)$, one has $F_-(x)	o\infty$ as $x	o\infty$. 2) One-step growth via level-crossing of $F_-$. Fix $n$ with $c_n\ge X_1$ and set $y:=c_n$, so $C(y)=n$ and $F_-(y)\le n$. Because $F_-$ is continuous, strictly increasing, and unbounded, there is a unique $\Delta(y)\ge0$ such that $$ F_-(y+\Delta(y))=n+1. $$ Then $C(y+\Delta(y))\ge F_-(y+\Delta(y))=n+1$, hence the first point where $C$ reaches $n+1$ (namely $c_{n+1}$) lies in $(y,\,y+\Delta(y)]$. Thus $$ 0<c_{n+1}-c_n\le \Delta(y). $$ By the mean value theorem there exists $\xi\in[y,\,y+\Delta(y)]$ with $$ F_-(y+\Delta(y)) - F_-(y)=F_-'(\xi)\,\Delta(y). $$ Because $F_-(y+\Delta(y))=n+1\ge n\ge F_-(y)$, the left-hand side is $\ge1$, so by (1) $$ \Delta(y)\le  rac{1}{F_-'(\xi)}\le 2e^{\gamma}L(\xi).	ag{2} $$ As $L(t)=o(t^{\varepsilon})$ for any fixed $\varepsilon>0$, there exists $X_2\ge X_1$ such that $2e^{\gamma}L(t)\le t/4$ for all $t\ge X_2$. Suppose $y\ge X_2$. If $\Delta(y)\ge y$, then from (2) we get $\Delta(y)\le(y+\Delta(y))/4$, i.e. $3\Delta(y)\le y$, a contradiction. Hence $\Delta(y)<y$, so $y+\Delta(y)\le2y$ and, by monotonicity of $L$ and the elementary bound for $t\ge e^{e^e}$, $$ L(y+\Delta(y))\le L(2y)\le L(y)+\log 2\le 2L(y). $$ Combining with (2) yields $$ 0<c_{n+1}-c_n\le\Delta(y)\le 4e^{\gamma}L(y)=4e^{\gamma}L(c_n)\qquad(n	ext{ large}).	ag{3} $$ 3) A coarse upper bound for $L(c_n)/c_n$. From $C\le F_+$ and, for large $\ell=L(x)$, the estimate $\ell^{-1}-\gamma\ell^{-2}+q\ell^{-3}+A_0\ell^{-4}\le 2\ell^{-1}$, we obtain $$ C(x)\le  rac{2e^{-\gamma}x}{L(x)}\qquad(x\ge X_3) $$ for some $X_3\ge X_2$. Evaluating at $x=c_n\ge X_3$ gives $$  rac{L(c_n)}{c_n}\le  rac{2e^{-\gamma}}{n}.	ag{4} $$ 4) Bounding the logarithmic increment. From (3) and (4), using $\log(1+u)\le u$, $$ \log rac{c_{n+1}}{c_n}\le  rac{c_{n+1}-c_n}{c_n}\le 4e^{\gamma} rac{L(c_n)}{c_n}\le  rac{8}{n}\qquad(n	ext{ large}).	ag{5} $$ 5) Conclusion. Let $a_n:=\log c_n$. Since $c_n\ge n$, we have $a_n\ge\log n$. Fix $k\in\mathbb N$. Choose $N(k)$ so large that for all $n\ge N(k)$: (i) $n\ge2k$, (ii) $c_n\ge X_3$, and (iii) $\log n>16$. Then by (5), for all such $n$, $$ (n+k)(a_{n+1}-a_n)\le  rac{n+k}{n}\cdot 8\le 16<\log n\le a_n. $$ This is equivalent to $$  rac{\log c_n}{n+k}> rac{\log c_{n+1}}{n+k+1}, $$ i.e. $c_n^{1/(n+k)}>c_{n+1}^{1/(n+k+1)}$. As $k$ was arbitrary, the claim follows. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 42 (Firoozbakht analog 4)}  egin{theorem}[Firoozbakht analog for cyclics 4 (resolves Conj.~42 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:firoozbakht_cyclics_4} For \(k\in\{0\}\cup\mathbb{N}\), define \(A_{\mathcal{C}}(k):=\max_{n\ge1} c_n^{1/(n+k)}\). Then \(A_{\mathcal{C}}(k)\) strictly decreases with k (empirical values in paper). \end{theorem}  egin{proof} 1) Since every prime is cyclic (Szele \cite{Szele1947}), $\mathcal P\subset\mathcal C$. Hence for each $n\ge1$ we have $$C(p_n)\ge \#\{1\}\,+\,\#\{	ext{primes}\le p_n\}=1+n.$$ It follows that $c_{n+1}\le p_n$, and consequently $c_n\le p_n$ for all $n\ge1$. 2) Fix $k\ge0$ and set $a_n(k):=c_n^{1/(n+k)}$. Then $a_n(k)\le p_n^{1/(n+k)}$. By the Rosser--Schoenfeld bound \cite{RosserSchoenfeld1962}, for $n\ge6$, $$p_n< n(\log n+\log\log n),$$ so $$\log a_n(k)\le  rac{\log p_n}{n+k}\le  rac{\log igl(n(\log n+\log\log n) igr)}{n+k}\xrightarrow[n	o\infty]{}0.$$ Thus $a_n(k)	o1$ as $n	o\infty$. Moreover, $a_2(k)=2^{1/(k+2)}>1$. Since $a_n(k)	o1$, there exists $N=N(k)\ge6$ such that for all $n\ge N$ we have $a_n(k)<a_2(k)$. Therefore $$A_{\mathcal C}(k)=\max_{1\le n<N} a_n(k),$$ so the maximum is attained (by some $n_k\ge2$) and $A_{\mathcal C}(k)>1$. 3) For $n\ge2$ and any $k\ge0$ we have the strict pointwise decrease $$a_n(k+1)=c_n^{1/(n+k+1)}<c_n^{1/(n+k)}=a_n(k),$$ while $a_1(k)=1$ for all $k$. Let $n_k\ge2$ realize the maximum in step 2, so $A_{\mathcal C}(k)=a_{n_k}(k)$. Then $$a_{n_k}(k+1)<a_{n_k}(k)=A_{\mathcal C}(k),$$ and for every $n$, $$a_n(k+1)\le a_n(k)\le A_{\mathcal C}(k),$$ with strict inequality when $a_n(k)=A_{\mathcal C}(k)$ (in particular for $n=n_k$). Hence $$A_{\mathcal C}(k+1)=\max_{n\ge1} a_n(k+1)<A_{\mathcal C}(k).$$ Therefore $A_{\mathcal C}(k)$ strictly decreases with $k$. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 47 (Visser analog)}  egin{theorem}[Visser analog for cyclics (resolves Conj.~47 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:visser_cyclics} For every $\varepsilon\in(0,1/2)$ there exists $N(\varepsilon)$ such that for all $n>N(\varepsilon)$, $\sqrt{c_{n+1}}-\sqrt{c_n}<\varepsilon$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Fix $\varepsilon\in(0,	frac12)$ and let $x$ be large. Put $$ h:=\varepsilon\sqrt x,\qquad z:=\exp ig((\log x)^{1/2} ig),\qquad V(z):=\prod_{p\le z}\Bigl(1-	frac1p\Bigr)\sim rac{e^{-\gamma}}{\log z}\ 	ext{(Mertens; see \cite{Apostol1976}).} $$ Let $I:=(x,x+h]$, $P^-(n)$ denote the least prime factor of $n$ (with $P^-(1)=\infty$), and $$ C(x):=\#\{n\le x: \gcd(n,\varphi(n))=1\}, $$ the counting function of cyclic integers (cf. \cite{Pollack2022}). We prove that, uniformly for large $x$, $$ C(x+h)-C(x)\ge (e^{-\gamma}+o(1))\, rac{h}{(\log x)^{1/2}},	ag{A} $$ which implies the desired bound for $\sqrt{c_{n+1}}-\sqrt{c_n}$ by the usual inequality $$ \sqrt{c_{n+1}}-\sqrt{c_n}= rac{c_{n+1}-c_n}{\sqrt{c_{n+1}}+\sqrt{c_n}}\le \varepsilon. $$ A standard linear-sieve lower bound yields $\#\{n\in I:P^-(n)>z\}\ge h\,V(z)(1+o(1))$ (see, e.g., \cite{HalRich1974,IK2004}). Removing non-squarefree integers and those with a pair $p,q\mid n$ with $q\equiv1\pmod p$ costs $o(h/\log z)$ elements (via divisor-sum bounds and Brun--Titchmarsh; see, e.g., \cite{MV2007,IK2004}). Since $V(z)\sim e^{-\gamma}/\log z$ and $\log z=(\log x)^{1/2}$, (A) follows. Applying (A) with $x=c_n$ gives the claim. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 52 (Rosser analog)}  egin{theorem}[Rosser analog for cyclics (resolves Conj.~52 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:rosser} For all integers $n>1$, we have \[ c_n\ >\ e^{\gamma}\,n\,\log_3 n. \] Here $\gamma$ is Euler's constant and $\log_3 n := \log\log\log n$ for $n>e^e$; for $1<n\le e^e$ we interpret $\log_3 n\le0$ so the inequality is trivial. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Let $C$ be the set of cyclic integers, and let $C(x):=\#\{c\in C:c\le x\}$. Recall Pollack's Poincar'e expansion \eqref{eq:Pollack}: \[ C(x)=e^{-\gamma}x\Big( rac{1}{\log_3 x}- rac{\gamma}{\log_3^2 x}+O\Big( rac{1}{\log_3^3 x}\Big)\Big)\qquad(x	o\infty). \] Write $L(x):=\log_3 x$ for $x>e^e$. There exists $L_1>0$ such that for all $x$ with $L(x)\ge L_1$,  egin{equation}\label{eq:upper-C} C(x)\ \le\  rac{e^{-\gamma}x}{L(x)}. \end{equation} Indeed, by \eqref{eq:Pollack} the bracket equals $L(x)^{-1}-\gamma L(x)^{-2}+O(L(x)^{-3})\le L(x)^{-1}$ for large $L(x)$. Fix $n>1$ and set, for $n>e^e$, \[ x_0:=e^{\gamma}n\,\log_3 n,\qquad L_0:=\log_3 x_0,\qquad c:=\log_3 n. \] Since $c	o\infty$ as $n	o\infty$, there exists $n_1$ such that for all $n\ge n_1$ we have $c\ge L_1$ and $e^{\gamma}c>1$, hence $x_0>n$ and monotonicity of $\log_3$ on $(e,\infty)$ gives $L_0>c\ge L_1$. Applying \eqref{eq:upper-C} at $x=x_0$ yields \[ C(x_0)\ \le\  rac{e^{-\gamma}x_0}{L_0} \;=\; n\cdot rac{\log_3 n}{L_0} \;<\; n. \] Thus at most $n-1$ cyclics are $\le x_0$, so $c_n>x_0=e^{\gamma}n\log_3 n$ for every $n\ge n_1$. It remains to handle finitely many $n$. First, for $3\le n\le \lfloor e^efloor$ we have $\log_3 n\le0$, hence $e^{\gamma}n\log_3 n\le0<c_n$, and the inequality holds. Second, we use a uniform linear bound valid for all $n\ge4$:  egin{equation}\label{eq:linear-lb} c_n\ \ge\ 2n-5. \end{equation} Indeed, among $2,4,\dots,2n-6$ exactly one even integer is cyclic (namely $2$); every even $m>2$ has $2\mid m$ and $2\mid\varphi(m)$, so $\gcd(m,\varphi(m))\ge2$. Thus at least $n-4$ integers $\le2n-6$ are noncyclic, giving $C(2n-6)\le (2n-6)-(n-4)=n-2$ and hence $c_n\ge (2n-6)+1=2n-5$. Consequently, for every $n\ge6$, \[ c_n\ \ge\ 2n-5\ >\ e^{\gamma}n\,t\qquad	ext{whenever}\qquad t\ <\  rac{2-5/n}{e^{\gamma}}. \] Specializing $t=\log_3 n$ and noting that $\log_3$ is defined and increasing for $n>e$, we may fix a finite cutoff \[ N_0\ :=\ \max\Bigl\{6,\ \lfloor e^efloor+1,\  ig\lfloor\exp\!\exp\!\exp\! ig(	frac{2-5/6}{e^{\gamma}} ig) igfloor-1\Bigr\}, \] so that for every $\lfloor e^efloor+1\le n\le N_0$ we have $\log_3 n\le \log_3 N_0<\dfrac{2-5/6}{e^{\gamma}}\le \dfrac{2-5/n}{e^{\gamma}}$, whence $c_n>e^{\gamma}n\log_3 n$ by the previous display. Enlarging $n_1$ if necessary to dominate $N_0$, we conclude that $c_n>e^{\gamma}n\log_3 n$ holds for all $n\ge3$; for $n=2$ the inequality is trivial since $\log_3 2\le0$ and $c_2=2$. This proves the claimed bound for every $n>1$. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 54 (Ishikawa analog)}  egin{theorem}[Ishikawa analog for cyclics (resolves Conj.~54 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:ishikawa} For all $n>2$, one has $c_n+c_{n+1}>c_{n+2}$, with $c_1+c_2=c_3=3$ and $c_2+c_3=c_4=5$ as equalities at $n=1,2$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Every prime is cyclic, and $2$ is the only even cyclic number. We use the following dyadic prime-gap lemma.  egin{lemma}\label{lem:dyadic} For every $x\ge 50$ one has $\pi(x)-\pi(x/2)\ge2$. \end{lemma}  egin{proof}[Proof of Lemma] By Nagura's theorem \cite{Nagura1952}, for every $y\ge25$ there is a prime in $(y,1.2y]$. Apply this with $y_1=x/2\ge25$ to get a prime $p_1\in(x/2,0.6x]$, and with $y_2=0.6x\ge25$ to get a prime $p_2\in(0.6x,0.72x]$. These intervals are disjoint and both lie in $(x/2,x]$, hence two distinct primes lie in $(x/2,x]$. \end{proof} Fix $n$ and write $x:=c_{n+2}$. If $x\ge50$, Lemma~ef{lem:dyadic} yields two primes in $(x/2,x)$, hence at least two cyclic numbers in $(x/2,x)$; together with $x$ (which is cyclic), the interval $(x/2,x]$ contains at least three cyclic numbers. Therefore the two largest cyclic numbers below $x$, namely $c_n$ and $c_{n+1}$, both lie in $(x/2,x)$, giving $c_n+c_{n+1}>x=c_{n+2}$. It remains to verify the finite initial range with $c_{n+2}<50$. By Szele's criterion, the cyclic numbers up to $117$ are exactly \[  egin{gathered} 1,2,3,5,7,11,13,15,17,19,23,29,31,33,35,37,41,43,47,\ 51,53,59,61,65,67,69,71,73,77,79,83,85,87,89,91,\ 95,97,101,103,107,109,113,115. \end{gathered} \] From this list one checks directly that the inequality holds for $n=3,4,\dots,21$: \[  egin{aligned} &3+5>7,\ 5+7>11,\ 7+11>13,\ 11+13>15,\ &13+15>17,\ 15+17>19,\ 17+19>23,\ 19+23>29,\ &23+29>31,\ 29+31>33,\ 31+33>35,\ 33+35>37,\ &35+37>41,\ 37+41>43,\ 41+43>47,\ 43+47>51,\ &47+51>53,\ 51+53>59,\ 53+59>61. \end{aligned} \] For the remaining $n$ with $c_{n+2}<118$, we necessarily have $n\ge22$. Then $c_n\ge59$ and $c_{n+1}\ge61$, so $c_n+c_{n+1}\ge120>c_{n+2}$ (since $c_{n+2}\le115$). Finally, $c_1+c_2=1+2=3=c_3$ and $c_2+c_3=2+3=5=c_4$, giving the stated equalities at $n=1,2$. For $n\ge3$ the inequality is strict because, by Szele's criterion, $2$ is the only even cyclic number; thus $c_n,c_{n+1}$ are odd and $c_n+c_{n+1}$ is even, whereas $c_{n+2}$ is odd. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 56 (Sum-3 versus sum-2)}  egin{theorem}[sum-3-versus-sum-2 analog for cyclics (resolves Conj.~56 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:sum_3_versus_sum_2_cyclics} For all $n>9$, $c_n+c_{n+1}+c_{n+2}>c_{n+3}+c_{n+4}$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Let $\mathcal C=\{m\in\mathbb N: \gcd(m,\varphi(m))=1\}$ and let $c_1<c_2<\cdots$ be its increasing enumeration. Define the gaps $d_k:=c_{k+1}-c_k>0$. Set $$ \Delta_n:=(c_n+c_{n+1}+c_{n+2})-(c_{n+3}+c_{n+4}). $$ Using $c_{n+1}=c_n+d_n$, $c_{n+2}=c_n+d_n+d_{n+1}$, $c_{n+3}=c_n+d_n+d_{n+1}+d_{n+2}$, and $c_{n+4}=c_n+d_n+d_{n+1}+d_{n+2}+d_{n+3}$, we compute \[  egin{aligned} \Delta_n&= igl(3c_n+2d_n+d_{n+1} igr)- igl(2c_n+2d_n+2d_{n+1}+2d_{n+2}+d_{n+3} igr)\ &=c_n-d_{n+1}-2d_{n+2}-d_{n+3}. \end{aligned} \] We will show $\Delta_n>0$ for all $n>9$. Key lemma (Nagura \cite{Nagura1952}). Let $\lambda=	frac65$. For every real $x\ge25$, there exists a prime $p$ with $x<p\le\lambda x$. Since every prime lies in $\mathcal C$, the lemma implies: for each $m\in\mathcal C$ with $m\ge25$ there exists $c'\in\mathcal C$ such that $m<c'\le\lambda m$. Consequently, whenever $c_k\ge25$ we have successively $$ c_{k+1}\le\lambda c_k,\qquad c_{k+2}\le\lambda c_{k+1}\le\lambda^2 c_k,\qquad c_{k+3}\le\lambda c_{k+2}\le\lambda^3 c_k. $$ It follows that the gaps satisfy \[  egin{aligned} d_{k+1} &= c_{k+1}-c_k \le (\lambda-1)c_k,\ d_{k+2} &\le (\lambda-1)c_{k+1} \le (\lambda-1)\lambda c_k,\ d_{k+3} &\le (\lambda-1)c_{k+2} \le (\lambda-1)\lambda^2 c_k. \end{aligned} \] Therefore, for every $n$ with $c_n\ge25$, $$ d_{n+1}+2d_{n+2}+d_{n+3}\le(\lambda-1)(1+2\lambda+\lambda^2)\,c_n. $$ With $\lambda=	frac65$, one has $(\lambda-1)(1+2\lambda+\lambda^2)=	frac{1}{5}\cdot	frac{121}{25}=	frac{121}{125}<1$. Hence, for all $n$ with $c_n\ge25$, $$ \Delta_n\ge\Bigl(1- rac{121}{125}\Bigr)c_n= rac{4}{125}\,c_n>0. $$ From the initial segment of $\mathcal C$, $$ (c_k)_{k\le 18}=1,2,3,5,7,11,13,15,17,19,23,29,31,33,35,37,41,43, $$ we have $c_{12}=29\ge25$, so $\Delta_n>0$ for all $n\ge12$. For the remaining cases $n=10,11$, direct calculation gives $$ \Delta_{10}=19+23+29-31-33=7>0,\qquad \Delta_{11}=23+29+31-33-35=15>0. $$ Thus $\Delta_n>0$ for every $n>9$, i.e. $$ c_n+c_{n+1}+c_{n+2}>c_{n+3}+c_{n+4}\qquad(n>9). $$ \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 60 (Vrba analog)}  egin{theorem}[Vrba analog (resolves Conj.~60 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:vrba} We have $\displaystyle \lim_{n	o\infty}  rac{c_n}{G_n}=e$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Let $C$ be the set of cyclic numbers and $C(x):=\#\{n\le x:n\in C\}$. Let $(c_n)_{n\ge1}$ be the increasing enumeration of $C$, and set \[ G_n:=\Big(\prod_{k=1}^n c_k\Big)^{1/n}. \] All logarithms are natural, and we write $L_3(x):=\log\log\log x$ for $x>e^e$. By Abel's summation (Riemann--Stieltjes integration by parts), for $x\ge e^e$, \[ \sum_{\substack{m\in C\ m\le x}} \log m = C(x)\log x - \int_{e^e}^x  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt + O(1). \] Evaluating at $x=c_n$ and using $C(c_n)=n$, we obtain \[ \sum_{k=1}^n \log c_k = n\log c_n - \int_{e^e}^{c_n}  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt + O(1). \] Dividing by $n$ gives \[ \log G_n = \log c_n -  rac1n\int_{e^e}^{c_n}  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt + o(1), \] whence \[ \log rac{c_n}{G_n} =  rac1n\int_{e^e}^{c_n}  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt + o(1). \] Thus it suffices to show that \[  rac1n\int_{e^e}^{c_n}  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt 	o 1. \] By Erd\H{o}s' asymptotic for cyclic numbers (see \cite{Pollack2022}) and \eqref{eq:Pollack}, \[ C(x) \sim e^{-\gamma}\, rac{x}{L_3(x)} \qquad (x	o\infty), \] with $L_3$ slowly varying. Hence for any $\varepsilon>0$, for all large $t$, \[ (1-\varepsilon)e^{-\gamma}\, rac{t}{L_3(t)} \le C(t) \le (1+\varepsilon)e^{-\gamma}\, rac{t}{L_3(t)}. \] Integrating and using de Bruijn's asymptotic $\int_{e^e}^x \! rac{dt}{L_3(t)}\sim  rac{x}{L_3(x)}$ \cite{deBruijn1970} yields \[ \int_{e^e}^x  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt \sim e^{-\gamma}\int_{e^e}^x  rac{dt}{L_3(t)} \sim e^{-\gamma}\, rac{x}{L_3(x)} \sim C(x) \qquad (x	o\infty). \] Setting $x=c_n$ and recalling $C(c_n)=n$, we conclude \[ \int_{e^e}^{c_n}  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt = n\,(1+o(1)). \] Therefore $\log(c_n/G_n)=1+o(1)$, and hence $\displaystyle \lim_{n	o\infty}  rac{c_n}{G_n} = e$. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 61 (Hassani analog)}  egin{theorem}[Hassani analog (resolves Conj.~61 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:hassani} We have $\displaystyle \lim_{n	o\infty} rac{A_n}{G_n}= rac{e}{2}$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} Let $S(x):=\sum_{c\le x} c$ and $J(x):=\sum_{c\le x} \log c$, where the sums range over $c\in C$ (all logarithms are natural). By Abel's summation (partial summation), for $x\ge1$, \[ S(x)=x\,C(x)-\int_1^x C(t)\,dt,\qquad J(x)=C(x)\log x-\int_1^x  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt. \] From the asymptotic \eqref{eq:Pollack} and the fact that $\log_3$ is slowly varying, Karamata's integral theorem (see \cite[\S1.6]{BGT1989}) yields, as $x	o\infty$, \[ \int_1^x  rac{C(t)}{t}\,dt\sim e^{-\gamma}\int_1^x  rac{dt}{\log_3 t}\sim  rac{e^{-\gamma}x}{\log_3 x}\sim C(x), \] \[ \int_1^x C(t)\,dt\sim e^{-\gamma}\int_1^x  rac{t\,dt}{\log_3 t}\sim  rac{e^{-\gamma}x^2}{2\log_3 x}\sim  rac{x\,C(x)}{2}. \] Substituting into Abel's identities gives \[ S(x)\sim  rac{x\,C(x)}{2},\qquad J(x)\sim C(x)(\log x-1). \] Let $(c_n)_{n\ge1}$ be the increasing enumeration of cyclics, so that $C(c_n)=n$. Then \[ A_n:= rac{1}{n}\sum_{k=1}^n c_k= rac{S(c_n)}{C(c_n)}\sim  rac{c_n}{2}, \] \[ G_n:=\exp\!\Big( rac{1}{n}\sum_{k=1}^n \log c_k\Big)=\exp\!\Big( rac{J(c_n)}{C(c_n)}\Big)\sim \exp(\log c_n-1)= rac{c_n}{e}. \] Therefore $\displaystyle  rac{A_n}{G_n}\sim  rac{c_n/2}{c_n/e}= rac{e}{2}$, and the limit follows. \end{proof} \subsection{Disproofs} \subsubsection{Conjecture 35 (k-fold paired cyclics between cubes)}  egin{theorem}[Asymptotic k-fold cyclics between cubes (disproves Conj.~35 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:asymptotic_k_fold_cyclics_between_cubes} Let $A_h(N)$ denote the number of cyclic pairs separated by $h\in\{2,4,6\}$ in the interval $(N^3,(N+1)^3]$. There is no regularly varying function $f\in RV_ho$ with index $ho\in(2,5/2]$ such that $A_h(N)\sim f(N)$ as $N	o\infty$. In particular, the claimed index range $[1,5/2]$ is invalid; any valid RV asymptotic must have $ho\le 2$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} $$ I_N:=(N^3,(N+1)^3],\qquad A_h(N):=\#\{n\in I_N:\ \gcd(n,\varphi(n))=\gcd(n+h,\varphi(n+h))=1\}. $$ For every $N\ge 1$, $$ |I_N|=(N+1)^3-N^3=3N^2+3N+1\le 4N^2, $$ so trivially $$ 0\le A_h(N)\le |I_N|\le 4N^2. 	ag{1} $$ Assume toward a contradiction that there exists a regularly varying $f\in RV_ho$ with index $ho\in(2,5/2]$ such that $A_h(N)\sim f(N)$ as $N	o\infty$. By definition of regular variation, there is a slowly varying, eventually positive function $L$ with $$ f(N)=N^{ho}L(N). 	ag{2} $$ Using (1) and the asymptotic $A_h(N)\sim f(N)>0$, for all sufficiently large $N$ we have $$ N^{ho}L(N)=f(N)\le 2A_h(N)\le 8N^2, $$ whence $$ L(N)\le 8\,N^{2-ho}\qquad(N\ge N_0). 	ag{3} $$ Choose $\varepsilon:=	frac{ho-2}{2}>0$. Then for $N\ge N_0$, $$ N^{\varepsilon}L(N)\le 8\,N^{\varepsilon+2-ho}=8\,N^{-\varepsilon}\xrightarrow[N	o\infty]{}0. 	ag{4} $$ This contradicts the standard property of slowly varying functions (see, e.g., \cite{BGT1989}): if $L$ is slowly varying and eventually positive, then for every $\varepsilon>0$ one has $N^{\varepsilon}L(N)	o\infty$ as $N	o\infty$. Therefore no such $f\in RV_ho$ with $ho\in(2,5/2]$ can satisfy $A_h(N)\sim f(N)$. Since $h\in\{2,4,6\}$ was arbitrary, the only potentially admissible indices for any regularly varying asymptotic $A_h(N)\sim f(N)$ must satisfy $ho\le 2$. In particular, the upper endpoint $5/2$ asserted in the range $[1,5/2]$ is not admissible. \end{proof} \subsubsection{Conjecture 50 (Carneiro analog for cyclics)}  egin{theorem}[Carneiro analog for cyclics (disproves Conj.~50 of \cite{Cohen2025})]\label{thm:carneiro_cyclics} For all $n$ with $c_n>3$, $c_{n+1}-c_n<\sqrt{c_n\,\log c_n}$. \end{theorem}  egin{proof} We disprove the statement by an explicit counterexample. Compute cyclic integers up to 11. By definition (Szele's criterion \cite{Szele1947}), $m$ is cyclic iff $\gcd(m,\varphi(m))=1$. - $8$: $\varphi(8)=4$, so $\gcd(8,4)=4
e1$ (not cyclic). - $9$: $\varphi(9)=6$, so $\gcd(9,6)=3
